complete_model_interaction.output:
Step-by-step reasoning:
• Key psychological mechanisms: In repeated decision‐making, participants tend to integrate available reward information (exploitation) and may be additionally influenced by the task “horizon” (longer free‐choice period may yield more exploratory behavior). In our task, participants learn the expected reward values for each option from past experience.
• How these mechanisms interact: The expected reward difference (option 1 minus option 0) drives exploitation, while the horizon manipulation (i.e. whether there are 6 free‐choice trials versus 1) can introduce an additive effect that increases/decreases the propensity to choose an option (possibly reflecting exploration). A bias term is also included.
• Mathematical form: A logistic decision function is used, with utility defined as a weighted linear combination of the difference in expected rewards, an additive horizon effect (implemented as a binary indicator: 1 for horizon==6, 0 for horizon==1), and an intercept bias.
• Parameters needed:
  – bias: captures an overall tendency to prefer one option (range set generously).
  – beta_er: scales how strongly the difference in expected rewards influences choice (must be positive).
  – beta_h: captures the additive effect of a longer horizon on choice (which can be either positive or negative).
• Mapping to observable behavior: The model uses the available expected reward estimates (expected_reward0 and expected_reward1) and the horizon condition (from the horizon variable) and predicts the probability of choosing option 1 when the trial is a free-choice. The target variable is the 'choice' (0/1).

Below is the formal mathematical model and variable description.

<MODEL>
P(choice=1) = 1/(1 + exp(-(bias + beta_er*(expected_reward1 - expected_reward0) + beta_h*horizonIndicator)))
</MODEL>

